  "text": "is study utilizes historical records to reconstruct past events and thus can be classi�ed as retrospective longitudinal research-an approach that has been considered as a practical alternative to the costly and inefficient panel-based longitudinal research [CITATION_1] . I selected Dragon Villas, a gated community in northeast Beijing, as the �eld site because of its long history and its presence of contacts. Evidence was primarily drawn from documents collected over eighteen years (1994) (1995) (1996) (1997) (1998) (1999) (2000) (2001) (2002) (2003) (2004) (2005) (2006) (2007) (2008) (2009) (2010) (2011) (2012) , including records of homeowners and tenants, meeting agendas, management expenditure statements, and internal memoranda of the management company. I also conducted twelve interviews between June and July 2012 with a diverse group of people that included the developer, the property manager, and several HOA members. e paper begins with a discussion on relevant government regulations in Beijing that constitutes the macrobackground of the case study. is discussion is followed by three sections that describe the case study. In each section, I demonstrate how a longitudinal perspective can reveal new insights. e �rst section examines the drivers of neighborhood democracy. e second section investigates the process of neighborhood democratization. e third section discusses the impact of neighborhood democracy. e paper concludes with a re�ection on the strengths and weaknesses of a longitudinal approach.",
